TITLE: Immigrant workers are helping boost the U.S. labor market
SUMMARY: The government predicts that the influx of immigrant workers will grow gross domestic product over the next decade by $7 trillion.

TITLE: Jobless rates rise in April for all racial groups except Black Americans
SUMMARY: The unemployment rate for Black Americans slid in April, bucking the trend in other demographic groups.

TITLE: U.S. job growth totaled 175,000 in April, much less than expected, while unemployment rose to 3.9%
SUMMARY: Markets had expected job growth of 240,000 and the unemployment rate to hold at 3.8%.

TITLE: Turkey's inflation accelerates to nearly 70% in April
SUMMARY: Turkey's inflation accelerated to 69.8% annually for the month of April, the Turkish Statistical Institute reported Friday.

TITLE: Here's what to expect from the April jobs report on Friday
SUMMARY: The Bureau of Labor Statistics report drops at 8:30 a.m. ET.

TITLE: UK to suffer slowest growth of all rich nations next year, OECD says
SUMMARY: The U.K.'s "sluggish" growth prospects have put it on course to be the worst-performing economy of all advanced nations next year, according to the OECD.

TITLE: BlackRock is opening a Saudi investment firm with initial $5 billion from PIF
SUMMARY: The new platform will be called BlackRock Riyadh Investment Management, or BRIM.

TITLE: Private payrolls increased by 192,000 in April, more than expected for resilient labor market
SUMMARY: Private payrolls increased at a faster than expected pace in April, indicating there are still plenty of tailwinds for the U.S. labor market.

TITLE: Here's everything to expect from the Fed meeting that will move markets on Wednesday
SUMMARY: Markets are anticipating a near-zero chance that the policy-setting arm of the central bank will announce any change to interest rates.

TITLE: McDonald's and other big brands warn that low-income consumers are starting to crack
SUMMARY: Higher prices have weighed on customers in an array of industries that interact with consumers.

TITLE: Worker pay rose more than expected in Q1 in another sign of persistent inflation
SUMMARY: The employment cost index, which measures worker salaries and benefits, gained 1.2% in the first quarter.

TITLE: Euro zone inflation steady at 2.4%, keeping June rate cut in play as economy returns to growth
SUMMARY: Price rises in the 20-nation euro area held steady at 2.4% in April, while the economy returned to growth in the first quarter.

TITLE: IMF chief warns of emerging market risk with high U.S. interest rates
SUMMARY: The benchmark rates of most advanced economies soared in recent years, as central banks aimed to tame inflation following the Covid-19 pandemic.

TITLE: Saudi Arabia says all NEOM megaprojects will go ahead as planned despite reports of scaling back
SUMMARY: "For NEOM, the projects, the intended scale is continuing as planned. There is no change in scale," Saudi Economy Minister Faisal Al Ibrahim told CNBC.

TITLE: WEF president:  'We haven't seen this kind of debt since the Napoleonic Wars'
SUMMARY: Borge Brende, president of the World Economic Forum, gave a stark outlook for the global economy.

TITLE: All the data so far is showing inflation isn't going away, and is making things tough on the Fed
SUMMARY: The last batch of inflation news that Federal Reserve officials will see before their meeting next week is in, and none of it is very good.

TITLE: Key Fed inflation measure rose 2.8% in March from a year ago, more than expected
SUMMARY: The core personal consumption expenditures price index was expected to increase 2.7% from a year ago in March, according to the Dow Jones consensus estimate.

TITLE: GDP growth slowed to a 1.6% rate in the first quarter, well below expectations
SUMMARY: Real GDP was expected to increase 2.4% in the first quarter on a seasonally adjusted basis, according to economists surveyed by Dow Jones.

TITLE: Why the Fed keeping rates higher for longer may not be such a bad thing
SUMMARY: It's a tough case to sell that higher interest rates today are having a substantially negative impact on the course of the economy.

TITLE: Something strange has been happening with jobless claims numbers lately
SUMMARY: For five of the past six weeks, the level of initial jobless filings totaled exactly 212,000.

TITLE: Risk of a global recession is minimal, IMF economist says — would take 'a lot to derail'
SUMMARY: The Washington DC-based institute this week nudged its global growth outlook slightly higher to 3.2% in 2024.

TITLE: High company valuations a 'worry,' IMF's capital markets chief says
SUMMARY: High corporate valuations could pose a significant risk to financial stability as market optimism becomes untethered from fundamentals, the IMF said Tuesday.

TITLE: UK inflation eases less than expected to 3.2% in March, sparking concerns of U.S.-style stickiness
SUMMARY: Economists polled by Reuters expected a reading of 3.1%, down from 3.4% in February.

TITLE: IMF upgrades global growth forecast as economy proves 'surprisingly resilient' despite downside risks
SUMMARY: The IMF on Tuesday raised its global growth forecast slightly, saying the economy had proven "surprisingly resilient" despite inflationary pressures.

TITLE: U.S. economy will see 'more things break' in 2025 if rates stay high, strategist says
SUMMARY: Altaf Kassam told CNBC that classic monetary policy mechanisms had "broken."

TITLE: Retail sales jumped 0.7% in March, much higher than expected
SUMMARY: Retail sales increased 0.7% for the month, considerably faster than the Dow Jones consensus forecast for a 0.3% increase.

TITLE: Surging inflation fears sent markets tumbling and Fed officials scrambling
SUMMARY: The early data is in for the path of inflation during the first three months of 2024, and the news so far is not good.

TITLE: Beyoncé bounce: Western boot sales jump more than 20% week over week since 'Cowboy Carter' launch
SUMMARY: The iconic shoe is getting a lift from Beyoncé's latest album.

TITLE: BlackRock's Larry Fink sees Fed cutting rates twice this year but missing 2% inflation goal
SUMMARY: The head of the world's largest money manager said it's unlikely the central bank will hit its 2% goal anytime soon.

TITLE: Jamie Dimon warns that inflation, wars and Fed policy pose major threats ahead
SUMMARY: Taken together, Dimon said the three issues pose substantial unknowns.
